WASHINGTON (Reuters) - The U.S. Congress struggled to produce a fresh coronavirus relief bill on Monday, as a stubborn standoff between Republicans and Democrats complicated the challenge of passing legislation with most lawmakers out of town.
Democrats and state governors also want to include aid to help state governments on the front line of the outbreak.
Aides to Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell and House Republican leader Kevin McCarthy declined to comment.
With Congress on recess and much of the country shut down, congressional leaders have tried to avoid calling members back to Washington.
